{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_coleman_ver02/data/sn86063730/00332894754/1927032001/0192.xml":{"full_text":"CLAIMS TEXAS\nDETOURS WILL\nBE ELIMINATED\nContractors Required\nTo Provide Goon\nRoads Around Con\nstruction Work\nFORT WORTH, Tex., March 19\u2014\nThe days of long, tiresome detours\naround new highway construction in\nTexas, a source of considerable an\nnoyance, delay and expense to motor\nists in past years, are drawing to a\nclone, it was announced at the of\ntic of the Highway Club of Texas\nhere todav\nIn th< .-iture,-it was stated, con\ntractors are to be required to pro\nvide adequate and passable detours\nbefore beginning construction work\non main highways, and also will be\nr quired to properly maintain the\ndetour throughout the construction\nperiod, the costs incident thereto\nbeing included in the contract price\nof the new road.\nThis is in accordance with a policy\nadopted in l'.*2i) by the United\nStates Bureau of Public Roads when\nThomas M. McI>o* Id, chief of the\nbureau, declared that highways are\nfor the use and benefit of the public,\nthat highway construction is inci\ndent thereto, and that traffic must\nbe taken care of. The bureau chief\nfurther ruled that the Federal Gov\nernment could participate in the\ncost of detour maintenance.\nA bill requiring adequate d?tours\nin Texas was introduced in the pres\nent session of the Legislature, at \u2019he\ninstance of thi* Highway Club, but\nthe pres* of other matters makes it\nimprobable that it will be finally\nacted uoon before the expected\nSpeci;\u2019l Session, probably in April.\nOfficers of the club, however, have\nbeen informed by Hon. Cone John\nson, a pieinbor of the State Highway\nCommission, that the present aumin-!\nistration will pursue such a policy,\nregardless of whether or not tae b ii\nis passed.\n\"Jlv highway Commission deserv\nes the commendation of the motor\ning public for the adoption of such\na policy/\u2019 it was stated at the High-'\nClub offices, \u201cbecause it shows con\nclusively that the in robers recog\nnize, as the federal Government ha*,'\nthe tact that the public is entitled\nto a passable road at ail\u2018times, re\ngardless of the fa<*t that a new j\nhighway is under construction.\nI in this connection, it was pointed\nout such a policy hue long been fol\nlowed in the operation ot railroa.ii. 1\nin the case ot wjreeks or washout*\nblocking progrefk on the i.^aiar\nline, no trouble or expense is spar\ned in dc-touting trams over other\nlines until repairs can b. made nr.d\nthe routing resumed. Often u.h\ndetours are effected without the\nKnowledge of passi ng *r<5.\nA plan which has been used with\nsuccess in several Caste rn states\nmay be tried out in Texas ns a re\nsult of this policy on the putt of the\nHighway Commission. Th plan pro\nvides lor the closing of only one\nhalf of the mam highway at a time,\niu the case of a 30-foot highway, a\nI 15 foot strip would Lc rlo-*..<i wail*'\nthe new construction wa- under way,\nleaving the other 15 feet open for\ntraffic. When the first half of the\ntoad is completed, it is opened for\ntraffic, then the other half olo.ed\nami rebuilt.\nHtill another has b en tried with\nsuccess in Louisiana, where a quick\ncuring paving material w.v I ing\ni used. Portable wooden bridge* ver\nconstructed and placed i-r the\nditches on either side of the road\nwhere con troction v.a* anm r way.\nTraffic thus was permitted to con\ntinue on the main highw y until it\nleeched the point of actual construe\nj tion woik, when it war- diverted over\ni the wooilen bridges for oine 2#*)\nfeet, thence back on to the main\nhighway again. The wooden brulg\nes were moved along a the construe\nII tion work progre cd, ciiU' in no d\nlay to traffic whatever because of\nthe construction w..rK.\nLOVE SI'H lin AT ID\ni WH AGO. Mias harlot*\n\u00bblfed 4\u00bb. committed suicide bfcaust\nshe had fallen in love with a mar\nried man.\nWHO IS THIS\nGAL-ETHYL?\nEthyl Now Invading\nWest After Con\nquerin